'''Ōi Clan''' (大井氏) refers to various Japanese clans: * {{ill|Ki Clan|ja|紀氏|1=Kii no Kuni no Miyatsuko|de|Ki (Klan)|uk|Рід Кі|ko|기씨 (황별)|fr|Kii no Kuni no Miyatsuko|3=紀伊国造|12=draft|12=draft}}, including figures such as {{ill|Ōi Sanespring|ja|大井実春|12=draft|12=draft}}. * A cadet branch of the {{ill|Shinano Minamoto|ja|信濃源氏|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Ogasawara Clan|ja|小笠原氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, who also served as deputy governors of {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|12=draft|12=draft}}. * A cadet branch of the {{ill|Kai Minamoto|ja|甲斐源氏|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Takeda Clan|ja|武田氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. * A family belonging to the {{ill|Murayama Party|ja|村山党|12=draft|12=draft}}, one of the {{ill|Seven Parties of Musashi|ja|武蔵七党|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Ōi Clan (Ki Clan) ==
The branch of the {{ill|Ki Clan|ja|紀氏|1=Kii no Kuni no Miyatsuko|de|Ki (Klan)|uk|Рід Кі|ko|기씨 (황별)|fr|Kii no Kuni no Miyatsuko|3=紀伊国造|12=draft|12=draft}} descending from the {{ill|Ki Nagahaseo|ja|紀長谷雄|12=draft|12=draft}} line settled in {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国|12=draft|12=draft}} during the time of {{ill|Ki Saneokina|ja|紀実直|12=draft|12=draft}}, associated with provincial government offices. They had deep ties with {{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国|12=draft|12=draft}}. Apart from the Ōi Clan, their relatives included the {{ill|Shinagawa Clan|ja|品川氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kasukabe Clan|ja|春日部氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tsutsumi Clan|ja|堤氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Shioda Clan|ja|潮田氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is believed that the Kasukabe Clan served {{ill|Minamoto no Yorimasa|ja|源頼政|12=draft|12=draft}}.
{{ill|Ōi Sanespring|ja|大井実春|12=draft|12=draft}} participated in the suppression of the remnants of the {{ill|Taira Clan|ja|平氏|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国|12=draft|12=draft}}, including {{ill|Shida Yoshihiro|ja|志田義広|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hirata Ietoki|ja|平田家継|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Taira no Nobukane|ja|平信兼|12=draft|12=draft}} in the third year of {{ill|Juei|ja|寿永|12=draft|12=draft}} (1184). In {{ill|Gennya|ja|元暦|12=draft|12=draft}} 2 (1184), he performed ceremonial duties for {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshitsune|ja|源義経|12=draft|12=draft}}. By {{ill|Bunji|ja|文治|12=draft|12=draft}} 1 (1185), he had been granted fiefs, including the {{ill|Katori District|ja|香取郡|12=draft|12=draft}} in present-day {{ill|Kuwana City|ja|桑名市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Mie Prefecture, and later parts of {{ill|Ōi District|ja|大井郷|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Ōmori District|ja|大森郷|12=draft|12=draft}}. The Ōi Clan remained loyal retainers of {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|12=draft|12=draft}} and were treated favorably. Sanespring was renowned for his strength, participating in sumo matches before Yoritomo.
; References * {{Cite book|author=Ochiai Yoshiaki|title=The Urban Settings and Samurai of the Medieval Eastern Provinces|year=2005|isbn=978-4634523418}} * {{Cite book|author=Noguchi Minoru|title=Eastern Samurai and Kyoto|year=2015|isbn=978-4886217110}}
== Ōi Clan (Ogasawara Lineage) ==
The Ōi Clan of Shinano Province originates from {{ill|Ogasawara Nagakiyo|ja|小笠原長清|12=draft|12=draft}}'s seventh son, {{ill|Ōi Tomomitsu|ja|大井朝光|12=draft|12=draft}}, who settled in {{ill|Ōi Manor|ja|大井荘 (信濃国)|12=draft|12=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Saku City|ja|佐久市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Nagano Prefecture) following his contributions in the {{ill|Jōkyū Rebellion|ja|承久の乱|12=draft|12=draft}}. Tomomitsu’s descendants expanded their influence in {{ill|Saku District|ja|佐久郡|12=draft|12=draft}} and allied with prominent clans.
=== Timeline === * {{ill|Kengen|ja|建仁|12=draft|12=draft}} 1 (1275): Financial contributions to {{ill|Wakamiyahachimangu Shrine|ja|若宮八幡宮社|12=draft|12=draft}} were recorded. * {{ill|Kōan|ja|弘安|12=draft|12=draft}} 8 (1285): The fall of the {{ill|Banno Clan|ja|伴野氏|12=draft|12=draft}} marked a significant power shift in Saku.
Despite facing challenges during the {{ill|Nanboku-chō Period|ja|南北朝時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the Ōi Clan remained influential, continuing to expand under the governance of the {{ill|Ashikaga Clan|ja|足利氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. However, their power waned after the defeat during the {{ill|Ōtō Conflict|ja|大塔合戦|12=draft|12=draft}}.
=== Genealogy === {{familytree/start}} {{familytree|n1=Ogasawara Nagakiyo|n2=Tomomitsu}} {{familytree/end}}
== Ōi Clan (Takeda Lineage) ==
The Ōi Clan in {{ill|Kai Province|ja|甲斐国|12=draft|12=draft}} centered around {{ill|Ōi Manor|ja|大井荘 (甲斐国)|12=draft|12=draft}}. It served as a cadet branch of the {{ill|Takeda Clan|ja|武田氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. During the {{ill|Muromachi Period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, they engaged in various battles alongside other regional clans such as the {{ill|Imagawa Clan|ja|今川氏|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Murakami Clan|ja|村上氏|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Notable figures include: * {{ill|Ōi Nobukiyo|ja|大井信清|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Ōi Shōji|ja|大井昌次|12=draft|12=draft}}
