{{ill|Ōi Sanespring|ja|大井実春|qq=draft|qq=draft}} participated in the suppression of the remnants of the {{ill|Taira Clan|ja|平氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, including {{ill|Shida Yoshihiro|ja|志田義広|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Hirata Ietoki|ja|平田家継|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Taira no Nobukane|ja|平信兼|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in the third year of {{ill|Juei|ja|寿永|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1184). In {{ill|Gennya|ja|元暦|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2 (1184), he performed ceremonial duties for {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshitsune|ja|源義経|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. By {{ill|Bunji|ja|文治|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (1185), he had been granted fiefs, including the {{ill|Katori District|ja|香取郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in present-day {{ill|Kuwana City|ja|桑名市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Mie Prefecture, and later parts of {{ill|Ōi District|ja|大井郷|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Ōmori District|ja|大森郷|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The Ōi Clan remained loyal retainers of {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and were treated favorably. Sanespring was renowned for his strength, participating in sumo matches before Yoritomo.
; References * {{Cite book|author=Ochiai Yoshiaki|title=The Urban Settings and Samurai of the Medieval Eastern Provinces|year=2005|isbn=978-4634523418}} * {{Cite book|author=Noguchi Minoru|title=Eastern Samurai and Kyoto|year=2015|isbn=978-4886217110}}
== Ōi Clan (Ogasawara Lineage) ==
The Ōi Clan of Shinano Province originates from {{ill|Ogasawara Nagakiyo|ja|小笠原長清|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s seventh son, {{ill|Ōi Tomomitsu|ja|大井朝光|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who settled in {{ill|Ōi Manor|ja|大井荘 (信濃国)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Saku City|ja|佐久市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Nagano Prefecture) following his contributions in the {{ill|Jōkyū Rebellion|ja|承久の乱|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Tomomitsu’s descendants expanded their influence in {{ill|Saku District|ja|佐久郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and allied with prominent clans.
=== Timeline === * {{ill|Kengen|ja|建仁|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (1275): Financial contributions to {{ill|Wakamiyahachimangu Shrine|ja|若宮八幡宮社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were recorded. * {{ill|Kōan|ja|弘安|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 8 (1285): The fall of the {{ill|Banno Clan|ja|伴野氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} marked a significant power shift in Saku.
Despite facing challenges during the {{ill|Nanboku-chō Period|ja|南北朝時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the Ōi Clan remained influential, continuing to expand under the governance of the {{ill|Ashikaga Clan|ja|足利氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. However, their power waned after the defeat during the {{ill|Ōtō Conflict|ja|大塔合戦|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
=== Genealogy === {{familytree/start}} {{familytree|n1=Ogasawara Nagakiyo|n2=Tomomitsu}} {{familytree/end}}
== Ōi Clan (Takeda Lineage) ==
The Ōi Clan in {{ill|Kai Province|ja|甲斐国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} centered around {{ill|Ōi Manor|ja|大井荘 (甲斐国)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It served as a cadet branch of the {{ill|Takeda Clan|ja|武田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. During the {{ill|Muromachi Period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, they engaged in various battles alongside other regional clans such as the {{ill|Imagawa Clan|ja|今川氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Murakami Clan|ja|村上氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
Notable figures include: * {{ill|Ōi Nobukiyo|ja|大井信清|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Ōi Shōji|ja|大井昌次|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
