The Ōi Clan of Shinano Province originates from {{ill|Ogasawara Nagakiyo|ja|小笠原長清|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ogasawara Nagakiyo|qq=}}'s seventh son, {{ill|Ōi Tomomitsu|ja|大井朝光|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōi Tomomitsu|qq=}}, who settled in {{ill|Ōi Manor|ja|大井荘 (信濃国)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōi Manor|qq=}} (present-day {{ill|Saku City|ja|佐久市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saku City|qq=}}, Nagano Prefecture) following his contributions in the {{ill|Jōkyū Rebellion|ja|承久の乱|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkyū Rebellion|qq=}}. Tomomitsu’s descendants expanded their influence in {{ill|Saku District|ja|佐久郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saku District|qq=}} and allied with prominent clans.
=== Timeline === * {{ill|Kengen|ja|建仁|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kengen|qq=}} 1 (1275): Financial contributions to {{ill|Wakamiyahachimangu Shrine|ja|若宮八幡宮社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakamiyahachimangu Shrine|qq=}} were recorded. * {{ill|Kōan|ja|弘安|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōan|qq=}} 8 (1285): The fall of the {{ill|Banno Clan|ja|伴野氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Banno Clan|qq=}} marked a significant power shift in Saku.
Despite facing challenges during the {{ill|Nanboku-chō Period|ja|南北朝時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanboku-chō Period|qq=}}, the Ōi Clan remained influential, continuing to expand under the governance of the {{ill|Ashikaga Clan|ja|足利氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashikaga Clan|qq=}}. However, their power waned after the defeat during the {{ill|Ōtō Conflict|ja|大塔合戦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtō Conflict|qq=}}.
